{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Geoffrey Williams | image = | caption = | image_size = | birth_name = Geoffrey Williams | alias = | birth_date = 1963 | origin = London, England | death_date = | genre = [[soul music|Soul]], [[funk]], pop | occupation = Singer, songwriter, musician, [[Record producer|producer]] | years_active = 1984–present | instrument = Vocals, keyboards, guitar | label = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [[Polydor]], [[Giant Records (Warner)|Giant]], [[EMI]], Hands On Records, Movement Records, Oyster Music, Kobalt Music | website = [https://geoffreywilliams.wordpress.com/ geoffreywilliams.wordpress.com] }}
'''Geoffrey Williams''' is an English singer and songwriter. Five of his singles charted on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/27471/geoffrey-williams/|title=GEOFFREY WILLIAMS – full Official Chart History – Official Charts Company}}</ref> In the U.S., "It's Not a Love Thing", from his third album ''Bare'' (1992), reached No. 70 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Geoffrey Williams Top Songs |url=http://www.musicvf.com/Geoffrey+Williams.art |website=Music VF |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref><ref>''Billboard'', 12 April 1997, page 49: "The same night, R&B singer-songwriter Geoffrey Williams and his band gave a performance at London's Hanover Grand to launch his album 'The Drop' (Hands On Records). The gig ended with a version of his top 50 hit 'Drive,' which is ..."</ref>
==Discography== ===Albums=== *''Heroes, Spies and Gypsies'' (1988, [[Atlantic Records]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Geoffrey Williams – Heroes, Spies And Gypsies |url=https://www.discogs.com/Geoffrey-Williams-Heroes-Spies-And-Gypsies/release/3998272 |publisher=discogs |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> *''Prisoner of Love'' (1989, Atlantic) *''Bare'' (1992, [[Giant Records (Warner)|Giant Records]]/[[Reprise Records]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Geoffrey Williams – Bare |url=https://www.discogs.com/Geoffrey-Williams-Bare/release/3827906 |publisher=discogs |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> *''The Drop'' (1996, Hands On Records)<ref>{{cite web |title=Geoffrey Williams – The Drop |url=https://www.discogs.com/Geoffrey-Williams-The-Drop/release/4968763 |publisher=discogs |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> *''Move into Soul'' (2008, Oyster Music)<ref>{{cite web |title=Geoffrey Williams – Move into Soul |url=https://www.discogs.com/Geoffrey-Williams-Move-Into-Soul/release/6166332 |publisher=discogs |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> *''Yes Is the Answer!'' (2012, Kobalt Music)<ref>{{cite web |title=Geoffrey Williams – Yes Is The Answer! |url=https://www.discogs.com/Geoffrey-Williams-Yes-Is-The-Answer/release/6710148 |publisher=discogs |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>
===Singles=== *"I Want You to Stop (Calling Me Up)" (1984, Code Records) *"There's a Need in Me" (1987, [[Polydor]]) *"Cinderella" (1988, Polydor), Germany, No. 9 *"Lipstick" (1988, Atlantic) *"Prisoner of Love" (1989, Atlantic) *"Blue" (1989, Atlantic) *"It's Not a Love Thing" (1992, [[EMI]], UK; Giant/Reprise, U.S.) — [[UK Singles Chart|UK]], No. 63; [[Billboard Hot 100|U.S.]], No. 70 *"[[Summer Breeze (song)|Summer Breeze]]" (1992, EMI) — UK, No. 56 *"Deliver Me Up" (1992, Giant/Reprise) *"Sex Life" (1995, Hands On) — UK, No. 83 *"I Don't Want to Talk About It" (1995, Hands On) *"I Guess I Will Always Love You/Free Your Mind" (1995, Hands On) — UK, No. 91 *"I Guess I Will Always Love You" (1996, Hands On) — UK, No. 79 *"Drive" (1996, Hands On) — UK, No. 52 *"Sex Life" (1997, Hands On) — UK, No. 71 *"Somewhere on a Beach" (2005, Oyster Music)
