'''Frank C. Stanley''' (born '''William Stanley Grinsted''', 29 December 1868 – 12 December 1910)<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q4mXh7krTxkC&pg=PA55&dq=%22Frank+C+Stanley%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiStojih7_kAhU_VRUIHZveDgEQ6AEINTAC#v=onepage&q=%22Frank%20C%20Stanley%22&f=false  Frank Hoffmann, B Lee Cooper, Tim Gracyk, ''Popular American Recording Pioneers: 1895-1925'', Routledge, 2012, p.330]</ref> was a popular American singer, banjoist and recording artist active in the 1890s and the 1900s. 

William Stanley Grinsted was born on 29 December 1868 in [[Orange, New Jersey]]. He first recorded banjo solos under his own name in October 1891 for Edison<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/FirstBookOfPhonographRecords|title=First Book of Phonograph Records|publisher=Edison Phonograph Laboratory|year=1892|pages=190}}</ref> then began recording vocal records in 1898 for the [[National Phonograph Company|National]] and Norcross Phonograph Companies<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/EdisonStandardIndex/ESI#page/n5/mode/2up|title=Edison Standard Index|last=Deakins|first=Duane|year=1959|pages=V}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=August 1898|title=General News|url=https://archive.org/stream/phonoscope13hunt#page/n332/mode/1up/search/stanley|journal=Phonoscope|volume= 2| issue =  8|pages=11}}</ref> under the name Frank C. Stanley. He recorded prolifically for Columbia, Victor and Zonophone disc records between 1901 and 1910,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adp.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/talent/detail/28423/Stanley_Frank_C._vocalist_bass_vocal|title=Frank C. Stanley (vocalist : bass vocal)|website=Discography of American Historical Recordings}}</ref> alone and as a member of the Columbia and [[Peerless Quartet]]s. In 1904, The Peerless Quartet consisted of tenors Henry Burr and Albert Campbell, baritone Steve Porter, and bass Tom Daniels. In 1906 Frank C. Stanley replaced Daniels and assumed lead singing and managing responsibilities. He died of [[pleurisy]] on 12 December 1910 at his home in Orange. 
